        <cdwalite:descriptiveNoteWrap>
            <cdwalite:descriptiveNoteSet>
                <cdwalite:descriptiveNote>Stele from Asia Minor, early Roman imperial times. Diam. Top 20.5 cm, diam. below 25.5 cm, height 61 cm. Of desire, 
                    gray marble. Epitaph in Greek for a man named Seikilos. Tomb monument is from the 1st century AD. Of inscription, the last part is in the 
                    form of an anthem, and between the lines there is evidence node. Translated by Carsten Hoeg: Do not hide your light as long as you live, 
                    be sure never fully, life runs only a short while, eventually set a fixed date.</cdwalite:descriptiveNote>
                <cdwalite:sourceDescriptiveNote>http://samlinger.natmus.dk/AS/asset/7971/</cdwalite:sourceDescriptiveNote>
            </cdwalite:descriptiveNoteSet>
        </cdwalite:descriptiveNoteWrap>
        <cdwalite:inscriptionsWrap>
            <cdwalite:inscriptions>Εἰκὼν ἡ λίθος εἰμί. Τίθησί με Σείκιλος ἔνθα μνήμης ἀθανάτου σῆμα πολυχρόνιον.
                Ὅσον ζῇς φαίνου
                μηδὲν ὅλως σὺ λυποῦ
                πρὸς ὀλίγον ἐστὶ τὸ ζῆν
                τὸ τέλος ὁ χρόνος ἀπαιτεῖ.
                English translation:
                I am a tombstone, an icon. Seikilos placed me here as an eternal sign of the immortal memory.
                
                Do not hide your light so long as you live,
                make sure never fully,
                life runs only a short while,
                time sets a fixed term
                
                Seikilos Euterpe ...
            </cdwalite:inscriptions>
        </cdwalite:inscriptionsWrap>
